Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
addModulePort(25.10)                                      addModulePort(25.10)

Name
       addModulePort  - Adds a port or bussed port to a module, specified as a
       module or a hierarchical instance

Syntax
       addModulePort

       [-help]<moduleName>

       <portName><portDir>

       [-bus <n1>:<n2>]

       [-moduleBased]

       Adds a port or bussed port to a module, specified as a module or a  hi-
       erarchical instance.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes the type and default
              information for each addModulePort parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and all of its parame-
              ters, use the  man  command:

              man addModulePort

       -bus <n1>:<n2>
              Adds a bussed port to the module. Specify the bus range (the be-
              ginning and end of the bus). Use integers to specify the range.

              If the specified bus already exists, tool will do bus bit resiz-
              ing. The specified bus bit range must be adjacent to  the  first
              or the last bit of the existing bus. Also, it must have the same
              ascending or descending order as the existing bus.

       -moduleBased
              Specifies if the port is module based.

       <moduleName>
              Specifies the name of a hierarchical instance, or a Verilog mod-
              ule  if  -moduleBased  is  specified, to which you want to add a
              port.  Specify "-" for the top hierarchical instance.

       <portDir>
              Specifies the port direction. You can specify the direction as:

              * input

              * output

              * bidi

       <portName>
              Specifies the name of the port to be added.

              The specified <portName> can be a new port name or  any  of  the
              existing  internal  net  names to which the port will connect in
              the module. Internal net means net  inside  the  module  without
              connections  to any existing port of the module. If the new port
              name is the same as the existing net name in the module, the net
              will not connect the port. The new port name will be portName_1.
              Port Name cannot be the same as any existing port  name  of  the
              same module.

              If  a bus port is added, the bit port name cannot be the same as
              any net name in the module.

Examples
              * The following command creates an input  port  p1  on  instance
                i1/i2/i3.  The  port  p1  must  be a new port name in instance
                i1/i2/i3. Instance i1/i2/i3 contains no nets name p1:

                addModulePort i1/i2/i3 p1 input

              * The following set of commands adds a  hierarchical  block  and
                then adds a bussed port to the block.

                addHierInst -cell i_block -hinst i_block1

                addModulePort i_block1 data output -bus 31:0

              * The  following  command adds two input bits i1[8] and i1[9] to
                existing top-level bus port i1[0:7].

                addModulePort - i1 input -bus 8:9

Related Information
              * addHierInst

              * deleteModulePort

